<paragraph blockId="15.[168,776,1585,2091]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018">
Therophyte, native with distribution in the Southern Cone Region of South America; previously reported from 
<collectingRegion box="[168,411,1799,1823]" country="Argentina" name="Buenos Aires" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018">Buenos Aires province</collectingRegion>
but not from mountainous areas.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="1018" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="15.[168,776,1585,2091]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[206,379,1832,1856]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018">Characteristics</emphasis>
: Annual herb, 
<quantity box="[545,641,1832,1856]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018" unit="cm" value="27.5" valueMax="50.0" valueMin="5.0">5–50 cm</quantity>
tall. Leaves linear, parallel-veined, to 
<quantity box="[454,524,1866,1890]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018" unit="cm" value="10.0">10 cm</quantity>
long, green, glabrous, with membranaceous ligule. Inflorescence: a spike-like panicle, to 
<quantity box="[285,338,1933,1957]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018" unit="cm" value="8.0">8 cm</quantity>
long, with many 1-flowered spikelets, ca 
<quantity box="[168,229,1967,1991]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
long; glumes unequal; lemma with 
<quantity box="[613,720,1966,1990]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.25" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="4.5" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018" unit="mm" value="5.25" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.5">4.5–6 mm</quantity>
long awns; palea absent. Fruit: a fusiform caryopsis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="1018" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[168,776,1585,2091]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[206,336,2033,2057]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018">Comments.</emphasis>
This is an infrequent species in the study area. It grows in shallow soils and rock cracks on the sum-
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[813,1420,1426,1550]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018">
mits. It is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Ness) Ness &amp; Meyen" authorityName="Ness &amp; Meyen" baseAuthorityName="Ness" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Bromidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hygrometricum">
<emphasis box="[1047,1339,1426,1450]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018">Bromidium hygrometricum</emphasis>
(Ness) Ness &amp; Meyen
</taxonomicName>
, which also has been found in 
<collectingRegion country="Argentina" name="Buenos Aires" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018">Buenos Aires province</collectingRegion>
, but 
<taxonomicName box="[1043,1241,1493,1517]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Bromidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hygrometricum">
<emphasis box="[1043,1241,1493,1517]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="1018">B. hygrometricum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a glabrous lemma.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
